This proportion varied substantially over space from 27.3% in the coastal area to only 12.8% in the High Maroni area, but did not vary significantly by sex (28.6% in ZIKV-positive women vs 21.8% in ZIKV-positive men; 
 P = .22). More than 95% of infected individuals who reported the occurrence of a presumptive ZIKV infection reported a year of occurrence between 2015 and 2017, corresponding to the period of transmission of ZIKV in French Guiana. Three-quarters of them (75.8%) declared that diagnosis was confirmed by a clinician and 54.7% declared that they had a laboratory confirmation. Fever (80.5%) and myalgia (62.4%) were the most frequently reported symptoms in ZIKV-positive participants. However, only rash (38.0%) and arthralgia (33.9%) were significantly more prevalent in ZIKV-positive individuals (
